,"about 1490":"okolo 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"okolo 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, Anglie","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1490–1536":"omkring 1490–1536","1490–1536":"1490–1536","1489–Female":"1489–Afdød","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1552–Female":"1552–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1468–Male":"1468–Afdød","1469–Female":"1469–Afdød","1536":"1536","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","about 1490":"omkring 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"omkring 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1490–1536":"circa 1490–1536","1490–1536":"1490–1536","1489–Female":"1489–Overleden","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1552–Female":"1552–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1468–Male":"1468–Overleden","1469–Female":"1469–Overleden","1536":"1536","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","about 1490":"circa 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"circa 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1490–1536":"about 1490–1536","1490–1536":"1490–1536","1489–Female":"1489–Deceased","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1552–Female":"1552–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1468–Male":"1468–Deceased","1469–Female":"1469–Deceased","1536":"1536","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","about 1490":"about 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"about 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clynton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Louth, Westmeath) and Scottish: shortened form of   McClinton  .","English: habitational name, either from Glympton in Oxfordshire, named as ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) on the Glym river’, a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright stream’, or from Glinton in Northamptonshire, early recorded as <i>Clinton</i> (named with an unrecorded Old English element akin to Middle Low German <i>glinde</i> ‘enclosure, fence’ + Old English <i>tūn</i>). The surname was taken to Ireland in or before the 16th century.","History: Charles Clinton (born 1690 in Longford, Ireland) organized a group of colonists and founded the settlement of Little Britain, Ulster County, NY, in 1731. His son George Clinton (1739–1812) was governor of NY (1777–95), and they had many prominent descendants. — An English aristocratic family called <i>Clinton</i> was founded by Geoffrey de Clinton (flourished 1130), who held lands at Glympton, Oxfordshire. He was chamberlain and treasurer to Henry I (1100–35)."],"variants":[{"name":"McClinton","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionntain</b> (Scottish), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntáin</b> (Irish) ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Fionntan</i>’, whose name has been explained as ‘the white ancient’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Clynton was christened about 1490, in Herefordshire, England, his father, John Clynton, was 23 and his mother, Alice Whittington, was 22. He had at least 7 sons and 5 daughters with Elizabeth Walwyn. He died in 1536, in Eastnor, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1490–1536":"umbes 1490–1536","1490–1536":"1490–1536","1489–Female":"1489–Surnud","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1552–Female":"1552–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1468–Male":"1468–Surnud","1469–Female":"1469–Surnud","1536":"1536","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"umbes 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1490–1536":"noin 1490–1536","1490–1536":"1490–1536","1489–Female":"1489–Kuollut","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1552–Female":"1552–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1468–Male":"1468–Kuollut","1469–Female":"1469–Kuollut","1536":"1536","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","about 1490":"noin 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"noin 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1490–1536":"environ 1490–1536","1490–1536":"1490–1536","1489–Female":"1489–Décédée","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1552–Female":"1552–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1468–Male":"1468–Décédé","1469–Female":"1469–Décédée","1536":"1536","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","about 1490":"environ 1490","1489":"1489","about 1514":"environ 1514","1575":"1575","1552":"1552","1490":"1490","Eastnor, Herefordshire, England":"Eastnor, Herefordshire, Angleterre","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Clynton a été baptisé environ 1490, à Herefordshire, Angleterre, son pèr